00:19:46.239 --> 00:19:47.239
else?

00:19:47.239 --> 00:19:56.040
Yeah, for sure. So there are, I'd say, the two components that I get new team members

00:19:56.040 --> 00:20:01.760
to focus on most heavily. The first is developing relationships. So there's a lot of get-to-know-you's

00:20:01.760 --> 00:20:08.560
at Target. You come work at Target, you see those all over your calendar. Whether I've

00:20:08.560 --> 00:20:12.560
been here for a few years, because we have new people coming on, and especially if it's

00:20:12.560 --> 00:20:18.760
your first month in role. But because I do index heavily on the relationship aspect,

00:20:18.760 --> 00:20:23.520
because I think the relationship will help facilitate communication, I say, let's make

00:20:23.520 --> 00:20:29.239
sure that you are getting to know our stakeholders better and our partners. So I'll set up a

00:20:29.239 --> 00:20:35.079
lot of those and make sure those copies are happening. And then on the technical side,

00:20:35.079 --> 00:20:41.359
we have the technical tools and the processes that we use. It's not incredibly diverse.

00:20:41.359 --> 00:20:46.040
We do use R and Python. I know some shops who are relatively small will just be an R

00:20:46.040 --> 00:20:53.239
shop or a Python shop, but we have a relatively small set of tools that we use. So I do have

00:20:53.239 --> 00:20:58.760
team members, and I think I always have on any team that I've built, who are very inclined

00:20:58.760 --> 00:21:03.479
to teach other people what they know. So you know who those people are on your team and

00:21:03.479 --> 00:21:07.040
you say, hey, this is your partner for the first month, or a new team member. This is

00:21:07.040 --> 00:21:10.760
your partner for the first month. They're going to show you the tools that you need

00:21:10.760 --> 00:21:15.119
to know, where the data is that you need to know. And then they'll also show you what

00:21:15.119 --> 00:21:20.119
we don't have today, because we do have limitations in our capabilities. And then when I check

00:21:20.119 --> 00:21:25.000
in, something I do, especially if it's a relatively new, if we have someone coming out of school

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:29.640
and it is their first job or their second job, they've only been in the workforce for

00:21:29.959 --> 00:21:34.839
I'll make sure to have a, right, personally, even if, right, I have senior managers under

00:21:34.839 --> 00:21:40.199
me, but if they're coming out, I'll make sure to have a 15 minute check in with them every

00:21:40.199 --> 00:21:45.800
day, right? Especially in virtual world, they might feel a little bit lost. So I'll have

00:21:45.800 --> 00:21:49.000
a 15 minute check in every day and kind of say, hey, who are you meeting? What do you

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:53.800
think? Did you, did you like them? Would you have another coffee with them? But then also,

00:21:53.800 --> 00:21:58.560
hey, what, what technical skills or what is what data set do you learn about today? Just

00:21:58.560 --> 00:21:59.560
to keep us aligned.

00:21:59.560 --> 00:22:06.479
Great. Thank you. This kind of, this question kind of goes back to what we were just talking

00:22:06.479 --> 00:22:12.079
