So personally, I have not used assignments. There's two, two different ways. So let me

00:22:27.119 --> 00:22:33.119
talk about the two different ways. So the first is I, I spent a year working at Wayfair

00:22:33.119 --> 00:22:37.839
and I think this is a habit I picked up from Wayfair because any, if you've ever gone on

00:22:37.839 --> 00:22:41.800
interview to Wayfair, you've probably been through a case question or a few case questions

00:22:41.800 --> 00:22:48.199
because they love that there. And I picked up the habit there and I feel like working

00:22:48.199 --> 00:22:52.239
with a potential candidate, no matter what level, we're just working through a case question,

00:22:52.239 --> 00:22:59.439
trying to solve a problem together and either do it on the whiteboard or you need to have

00:22:59.439 --> 00:23:05.359
a piece of paper and then you can show each other what you're writing down. You can identify

00:23:05.359 --> 00:23:12.359
a considerable amount of behavior and attitudes through doing that exercise with each other.

00:23:12.359 --> 00:23:16.880
And then also follow up questions is huge in the interview. So there's always the, let

00:23:16.880 --> 00:23:22.599
me ask you the first question and then if the candidate gives you an answer, always

00:23:22.599 --> 00:23:26.839
have a follow up question because I find if you can go a level deeper, that's kind of

00:23:26.839 --> 00:23:35.400
the more revealing segment. So case questions I'd say are number one. Number two, we, I

00:23:35.400 --> 00:23:42.599
had a partner that would, he had a linear regression interview question and it would

00:23:42.599 --> 00:23:46.760
be, hey, do you know R, do you know Python? People that could do this in Excel, great.

00:23:46.760 --> 00:23:50.719
I don't think anyone ever tried to do it in Excel, but it was a relatively basic linear,

00:23:50.719 --> 00:23:57.160
build a linear regression question and then go through it and talk through the ahas, oh,

00:23:57.160 --> 00:24:04.920
there's heteroscedasticity in the model that's going to throw us off and have candidates

00:24:04.920 --> 00:24:12.520
run through that. And you can kind of see how they think. And it really, really wasn't

00:24:12.520 --> 00:24:16.719
about can you do the code, right? Can you call the problem? It was more about how they

00:24:16.719 --> 00:24:22.640
think and how they try to, to navigate around the problem at hand. And I think that kind

00:24:22.640 --> 00:24:26.599
of brought out some of those behaviors that I had mentioned before going through that

00:24:26.599 --> 00:24:27.640
process.

